ted Kingdom":"Burnley, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Copenhall, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Lancanshire, England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1505–27 February 1586":"about 1505–27 February 1586","1505–1586":"1505–1586","1510–1570":"1510–1570","1531–1627":"1531–1627","1482–1581":"1482–1581","12 September 1570":"12 September 1570","1510":"1510","1531":"1531","1586":"1586","1530":"1530","1581":"1581","1482":"1482","1570":"1570","Abt 1505":"about 1505","27 February 1586":"27 February 1586","1627":"1627","1505":"1505",", , Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Coppenhall, Stafford, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stafford, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Burnley, Bury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Burnley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Copenhall, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Lancanshire, England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>s(c)hawe</i>, <i>s(c)haghe</i> ‘small wood, grove, thicket’ (Old English <i>sceaga</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a small wood, or habitational, for someone from any of the many places so named. <i>Shaw</i> and <i>Shawe</i> are most frequent in Lancashire and Yorkshire, where Shaw in Oldham (Lancashire) may be a principal source of the surname. The English and Lowland Scottish surname was also established in Ireland in the 17th century.","Scottish: shortened form of various surnames from the Gaelic personal name <i>Sitheach</i>, derived from <i>sithech</i> ‘wolf’.","Irish (Down and Antrim): adopted for <b>Ó Síthigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’. Compare   Sheehy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Show","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cumberland): probably a variant of   Shaw  , perhaps representing a blend in Middle English of Old English <i>sceaga</i> and Old Norse <i>skógr</i>, both meaning ‘wood’.","Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Schau  ."]},{"name":"Sheehy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Aisling, Brigid, Declan, Egan, Eoin, Finbar, Ronan.","Irish (Limerick and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Síthigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, or <b>Mac Síthigh</b> ‘son of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a form of the Irish personal name <i>Síodhach</i> ‘peaceful’, from the adjective <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’ or ‘other worldly’ (see   Sheehan  ). The noun <i>síth</i>, from which this adjective derives, means basically ‘settlement’, hence both ‘peace’ and ‘place inhabited by other world beings’. This name was established in Ireland from the early 14th century, when a branch of the Scottish McDonnells, descended from <i>Sítheach</i>, great-grandson of Domhnaill, settled in the country."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Shaw was born about 1505, in Stafford, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of John Shaw. He married Ellen Empson in 1530, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 27 February 1586, in Burnley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 82."},"et":{"Abt 1505–27 February 1586":"umbes 1505–27. veebruar 1586","1505–1586":"1505–1586","1510–1570":"1510–1570","1531–1627":"1531–1627","1482–1581":"1482–1581","12 September 1570":"12. september 1570","1510":"1510","1531":"1531","1586":"1586","1530":"1530","1581":"1581","1482":"